Excelente video cuya calidad atribuyo a dos factores. Por una parte al conocimiento a fondo de la IA evidenciado en especial cuando hablan de redes neuronales. Y por la otra a un dominio completo de las matemáticas. 

La maestría matemática queda ampliamente demostrada en el correcto tratamiento que hace vuestro canal de infinidad de cuestiones de álgebra, análisis y geometría, topología incluida.

Respecto a las redes neuronales cabe señalar que existe una manera alterna, poco divulgada, de obtener redes profundas de perceptrones, es decir redes con tres o más capas de perceptrones, similares a las que se calculan ajustando pesos mediante retropropagación de errores. 

Dicho método alternativo calcula la red profunda directamente a partir de los datos (ejemplos y contraejemplos) y de las franjas de separación deseadas en las hipersuperficies decisorias. Esta metodología inédita no utiliza para nada la retropropagación.

Se trata de un algoritmo, ya codificado en un programa y evaluado numéricamente, que se basa en formular los perceptrones en términos de categorías (objetos y morfismos) y en analizarlos en términos geométricos, todo lo cual permite un tratamiento transparente de la data numérica. 

El desempeño del algoritmo es notablemente más predecible, exacto y rápido que la retropropagación. Para una introducción a su uso sugiero que den un vistazo al siguiente video 
https://youtu.be/VTDIedU3F-E
en cuya descripción hallaréis un enlace para descargar el software (además de links a referencias), que corre en plataforma Windows, es totalmente gratuito y ni siquiera requiere instalación (es autoportante). Podréis probar el software con vuestros propios archivos de datos numéricos y comprobar a cabalidad que las redes así obtenidas reconocen exitosamente la data.

Felicitaciones por tan clara introducción a la IA y en particular a las redes neuronales.

There is so much thought put into this song

At first, the protagonist sounds very robotic, despite feeling almost every human emotion, indicating he is yet to reach desired level of being human. He felt them all but one - the need to send a photo of his genitals to some strangers. But does he really need to?

In the second chapter of the song, our hero is getting closer to reaching his goal. He experiences stronger feelings, like seeing his robot crush making out with robot douchebag. He goes home and sings how sad and alone he feels. This is the moment of transformation. He realizes, that the essence of humanity isn't just a set of rules, it is the ability to feel wide spectrum of emotions, simple and more complex ones, but also to be human is to be self-aware of how and why one feels a certain way (note how he says he is glad to be sad, because that means he does indeed feel real emotions). His voice also changes to sound more human-like - just like Pinocchio, he turns into a real boy. 

The third chapter tells another story - he is not a robot anymore, he is human (despite not feeling the need to send a dick pic). But there is one more thing he is not anymore - he is not pure of heart. His desire to become human turned him into a wannabe slaver. He claims to be superior to the human race because of said pictures (or lack of them). This is where we come full circle - the voice is again very robotic, indicating his descent into previous state, by which I mean being not-human. Is it because of his violent tendencies - can we call a human someone with such evil plans like enslaving the whole planet? Or does he turn into a robot by choice, after comprehending what he thinks it does mean to be human? Note how the song comes full circle, ending with the same verse it starts, almost identically, but being cut when we least anticipate it. Why does it end that way? Did the robot end himself? Or, since he considers himself a human now, or even something more, the song ends because he is no longer the subject of it? It leaves a nice space for interpretation, catalizing discussions and thoughts like this one.

Your music always excels at being more than just funny, and I love that. Like, it is funny, it is 90% goofy, jokey shitposts. But it's funny in a way that touches on something deeply human. Our tendencies to self-destruct, our messy and complicated relationships, our strange and unproductive expecations put upons both by outselves and the cultures and societies we grow up in. Ultimately, it's all about the strange, convoluted, absurd process of being human. And I think that, ironically, but making a song from the perspective of a being which is very much not human, it ends up being the perfect culmination of all those past themes.
This is EASILY your best work so far, and I am SO excited to see what the future holds.

I have a theory about a possible connection with 4055.
First, it struck me that "Robot Michelle" and "Robot Charlie" are odd names. Is the inclusion of "Robot" a neutral identifier or shows a social division between robots and humans?
We have few direct information on the status of Robots in the society of "Artificial Intelligence".
Robots are shown to have (almost) the full range of human emotions, have social interactions with humans (for it to be neccesary to avoid offending a possibly pregnant person) and have social media accounts, with which our protagonists tries to befriend humans at 1:55 (which also reveals that a robot can have respect and admiration for a human, and acquire their number), and also receives an unsolicited dickpic at 3:01.
On the other hand, robots have their own "robot parties", and most crucially, like shown at 1:55, are shunned and insulted by humans. "Robot fuck" and "Robot cunt" again is clearly othering language, which is persistent.
Overall robots seem to be very similar to humans and partake in society, yet also form a sub-society and are treated as other and inferior. In this light, our protagonist's desire to become human and obsession which becomes destructive also makes sense as internalized bigotry against robots (which could have also contributed to his isolation, melancholy and desperation)

Another detail about the shot at 1:55  is that the humans in question are named "mark and charlie". The choice to have the name Charlie appear twice (Robot Charlie) is also odd, though in isolation I didn't dare to openly speculate about it.
That changed when I watched 4055 and I had a possible lead for my intuitive hunch. In 4055, the first main character has a robot that looks exactly like him and which he forces to do chores and endure his abuse. A robot that looks exactly like him and belongs to him, could he also share his name?
Is Robot Charlie the robot doppelgänger of Charlie? "Robot Charlie" does sound more like "robot version of Charlie" then "a robot named Charlie".
Also 4055 features a robot revolt where a robot overlord (singular) enslaves the whole of humanity and quit his servitude after having shit thrown at his face (you could say, humanity's fucked up shit changed his mind). Could Artificial Intelligence show the full development of this robot overlord?
There's also nothing in Artificial Intelligence which would contradict all of humanity and robotkind living on a spacecraft, humans being cyborgs and other details from 4055.

Admittedly it's more complicated to link the two worlds. 4055 gives the impression of more extreme robot oppression. However, this impression isn't solidified with more details and one can fill the gaps of 4055 with the more nuanced worldbuilding of Artificial Intelligence without contradiction. 4055's first main character treats his robot very degradingly, but is chiefly motivated by boredom. Also considering how robots in 4055 look exactly like humans and have the emotional complexity to feel humiliation, it seems unlikely robots were created to just be mindless servants. So it's possible to imagine that robots in 4055 have a role in society more like in Artifical Intelligence. The first main character of 4055 could also show his human bias by being ignorant of robots' rich inner and social lives (which mirrors his apathy towards the sub-human farms)
Likewise, the protagonist of Artificial Intelligence turned pretty easily from being polite and trying to impress humans to wanting to enslave all of them, hinting that in the background there could be more serious human abuses against robots which he finally came to see for what it is.
Alternatively, it's also possible that there was more than one robot revolution (if the previous ones failed) and human-robot relations deteriorated strongly, leading to the conditions of 4055.

"Selected Stories" by E.M. Forster features rather-early sci-fi predicting that Artificial Intelligence would result in lack of imagination, exploration, or curiosity. It's the story "The Machine Stops".

I've heard people say, "If you're an artist/writer worried about AI taking your job, always remember that people will always prefer human-made over robot-made."

But those people forget that consumers don't care about whether a robot or a human made something, only if that something is good. If a robot managed to produce a work of literature with all the emotion, symbolism, imagination, craft, and skill of a human author, then people won't care if it was made by a machine. And we aren't that far from AI being able to produce works the replicate those things. I don't know what'll happen when that day comes.

I think this video raises very valud issues with AI. AI can defiantly be really cool and help us advance as a civilization, but if we overuse it or use it inadequately it can bring our ruin as well. Maybe we should just use it where it's obviously needed and useful, rather than a cheapskate trick to replace art, fire workers or do things in general we're either too lazy or to cheap to do ourselves.

First, let me say I'm not anti-tech (I'm a retired engineer), but I admit, I'm a little apprehensive about the wide spread use of AI and how there may be unintended consequences. Fortunately being 72 years old, I probably won't be around if 'the singularity' (in the 'out of control tech' sense of the word) occurs as a result.
The animation in these videos are always great but this animation has to be one of, if not my favorite. Wonderful job as always!

I say that AI should be either left untouched, or simply applied as a brainstormer that comes up with ideas but doesn't actually implement them.
This would allow us to sidestep many of the problems of AI, because then it won't actually do anything. It'll just help us figure out a variety of solutions. Perhaps after we've sufficiently advanced that sort of AI and gotten a hang of it, we could start dipping our toes into a more robust AI system.

 (Another one of the problems would be that the greater an AI's agency, especially if it should develop some form of emotions, the more important it'll be to give it ethics. And humans are pretty bad at ethics when we look at our track record.)

It is all good and well to just fantasize about how General Purpose AI (GPAI) will shape the world but the fact is that we're so far from achieving it that pretty much anything we say or predict  becomes instant Sci-Fi. So yeah we can fantasize about it knowing that we're doing just that but a disclaimer needs to be added when we present as if we can predict what will happen. Anything can happen, I can write 1000 scenarios but they will be equally implausible so let's not present them as if we know how AI is going to change the world. 

AI is definitely shaping the world as we speak but GPAI is all together a different beast that no one even come close to achieving it. Yes we have some large data trained GPT systems but they're just a good systems to put one word after another by looking at previous examples. It has no notion of what it is achieving. Plus, for a GPAI system to wreck havoc, it needs to be able to control outputs that can achieve that. You can always constrain a GPAI machine by limiting how it interacts with the external world by putting hardware switches that it cannot bypass by software or mechanical intervention. So doomsday scenarios are bit too overblown IMHO.

AI (Artificial Intelligence) is already changing the world in many ways and is expected to have an even greater impact in the future. Here are some ways in which AI is changing the world:

Automation: AI is making it possible to automate many tasks that were previously done by humans. This can increase efficiency and productivity, and also reduce costs.

Personalization: AI algorithms can analyze vast amounts of data to provide personalized recommendations and experiences for individuals.

Healthcare: AI is being used in healthcare to help diagnose diseases, develop new drugs, and improve patient outcomes.

Transportation: AI is being used to improve transportation systems, such as self-driving cars, drones, and traffic management systems.

Education: AI can personalize learning experiences for students and help teachers identify areas where students need extra help.

Customer Service: AI chatbots can provide 24/7 customer service and support, improving customer satisfaction and reducing costs for businesses.

Finance: AI is being used in finance for fraud detection, investment analysis, and risk management.

Overall, AI has the potential to revolutionize many industries and aspects of our lives, but it also raises important ethical and social questions that must be addressed.

I'm honestly terrified of AI and what it is capable of. Humanity in nature was meant to mosey around and live off of the land. AI may be the pinnacle of human civilization, because it could potentially enhance this machine we call civilization into something so uncontrollable that people wouldn't be able to adapt to it. Our priorities have become "efficiency" and "technological advancement", instead of nurturing humanity and building a world that is equitable, peaceful, and easy. Not to say that it is impossible nor possible to foster a global utopia, it's just that I think that we need heavy regulation on AI and tech, and to convince people that, just because we can make AI, doesn't mean that we should.

Regulations might be:
- Outlawing automated raw material extraction (disables self-replicative abilities for AI)
-Outlawing automated law enforcement 
-Outlawing automated military capabilities
-Outlawing automated judicial systems
-Outlawing AI in surveillance
-Installing automatic kill switches in all AI that are both digital and physical (phones and key-switches respectively)

Fundamentally, we need to create legal infrastructure that disables any capability for AI to self-replicate or involve itself in affairs pertaining directly to individual safety. Our only fighting chance at escaping a system that aims to enhance itself (SAI) is the fact that it may not possess the sufficient, raw resources to enhance itself. This cannot be the only barrier to regulating AI down to being a convenience tool.

EDIT: And if you don't believe me that we are sensible enough as a species to not let a "technological singularity" occur, then you've probably forgotten that we let world powers create nukes.

Nice presentation, but it's a bit nieve. I agree humans are constantly optimizing. For example, someone might suggest booking a southern route for winter travel - just in case there might be a snow storm. Some people call this "playing chess" because they are thinking a move ahead. And thinking a move ahead is exactly what computers are best at! Computers are so good at it, they have been OPTIMIZING complex problems for decades. Think of chess games and GPS navigation systems. Even 30 years ago, no one ever asked a chess computer to "forget the consequences, just make any legal move" or GPS system "take us anywhere, its OK if you drive on the sidewalk." Quite the contrary. Computers have been optimizing every step. And again, they have been doing this for decades. Why do people think computers will suddenly stop optimizing (ie "playing chess") as they get smarter. If anything, I see AI expanding the optimizing process rather than eliminating it. For example, I ask for a cup of coffee, and the AI says my blood pressure is too high for caffeine, so it brings me a bottle of water instead.

I think if and when computer science researchers arrive at the same proportionate level of understanding in quantum computing that they have now in traditional digital computation, the world of AI is going to explode. Right now if you teach an AI the 7-8 petabytes of knowledge needed to behave in the same way a human does, it's going to take way too much time and computational power for the AI to be useful. We also don't know how the AI is going to behave with that knowledge. There's no guarantee that it will be human-like. It probably won't. I get the metric of 7-8 petabytes from what neurosurgeons and computer scientists believe is the storage capacity for the human brain.

Add quantum computing into the mix though and things could potentially become way more efficient. A bit of data can be either a one, a zero or both. The speed of learning (writing), acting on (reading) and retrieving data could become exponentially faster. Task management and the additional considerations like coffee price mentioned in the video could be much more efficiently deduced. The possibilities with these two technologies coming together are endless. My suspicion is that we will reach this achievement but shrinking the hardware down to that of a human body equivalent is hundreds of years off. What might occur in the nearer future is space stations, air-craft, the biggest naval ships, space ships and large buildings will be able to draw power from nuclear reactors (fission in the next 100 years & fusion in the next 200 years) to provide the necessary power and cooling resources to make the AI function in a usable capacity.

The fundamental assumption here, that "AI doesn't know that it doesn't know everything about the true objective" is no longer true. Large transformer models have a lot more common sense than most people seem to understand. They do have real, serious limitations, including that they are extremely vulnerable to leading questions, they tend to hallucinate (make up "facts" that are not true), and they are not yet continuous learners. They are pre-trained, and only have short-term session memory, rather than long term learning memory. This is not because we don't know how to create continuous learners, but really for two reasons: 1. We want AI to progress in a slow-ish controlled manner. 2. Continuous learning is not yet efficient enough to scale well to large models.

The ending was extremely stupid in my opinion, but the overall fear that nothing really matters, that time will just destroy all of us, that they could just let 2000 years pass without really something happening to the protagonist, that this kind of suffering will never end, that stuck with me. I enjoyed watching this movie very much and even after all these years I remembered it quite well. But I am not sure what it is, if we leave we philosophy behind, what makes this movie so surreal. But then again, the flesh fair was just pure gore. I can´t understand how not more people were scared shitless of such violence and senseless torture.

I will choose my words carefully. These experiences are double edged swords. It may bring you a good experience but it also brings about a permanent 'scar memory' which I am not sure is something I really want.
I've had this feeling 3 times now. The first one was Dickens' David Copperfield. It took me a while to get the early part of David's life out of my head. 
The second one was, Sheldon's Doomsday conspiracy (Bellamy's separation), If Tomorrow Comes (Whitney's tragic jail life) and The Sands of Time ( Graciella's going back to nunhood).
The third time arguably is this blasphemous, jarring, scarring movie. 
But I must give credit. These have the power to scar me. 
But it should also be understood that being thoughtful, sensitive, understanding, deep etc is not something good for the individual with these traits.
